1) Build the sample obscure text program from here for Windows, MacOS, and Web :  https://api.flutter.dev/flutter/material/TextField-class.html
2) Use a voice over for Mac, and windows voice assistant to test the app on all 3 types
3) You'll notice the password is visibly  obscured, but read out loud by the voice readers. Except in the Web case.


For MacOS, [kSecureTextEntry](https://api.flutter.dev/ios-embedder/_flutter_text_input_plugin_8mm.html#a2551524a1b373099a3cf1bcf859da89c) seems to be used for obscureText, however I don't see it being checked anywhere when the textfield node is created. I think its created [here](https://api.flutter.dev/macos-embedder/_flutter_platform_node_delegate_mac_8mm_source.html)

For web it seems to be used [here](https://github.com/flutter/engine/blob/main/lib/web_ui/lib/src/engine/semantics/text_field.dart#L230), and is correctly checked and applied.

I expect we are missing a similar check for Windows, but I couldn't track that down.

