### Use case

Desktop apps often support keyboard shortcuts "chords" with multiple separate keypresses. Examples:

1. Visual Studio Code: `Ctrl+K` `Ctrl+O` opens a folder
2. Gmail: `g` `i` goes to the inbox

### Proposal

Add a new `ShortcutActivator` to support this. Strawman example:

```dart
// Activated by Ctrl+K followed by Ctrl+O
const openFolderActivator = ChordActivator(
  activators: <ShortcutActivator>[
    SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.keyK, control: true),
    SingleActivator(LogicalKeyboardKey.keyO, control: true),
  ],
);

return Shortcuts(
  shortcuts: const <ShortcutActivator, Intent>{
    openFolderActivator: OpenFolderIntent(),
  },
  child: ...,
);
```

## Use case

RawAutocomplete and Autocomplete will show options list on focus even if initialValue was provided.

## Proposal

Issue is that RawAutocomplete's _shouldShowOptions is dependent on _selection value:

    bool get _shouldShowOptions {
      return _focusNode.hasFocus && _selection == null && _options.isNotEmpty;
    }

but _selection is not initialized in initState. Attribute _selection is set only when value is actually seleted from options list:

    void _select(T nextSelection) {
      ...
      _selection = nextSelection;
      ...
    }

My proposal is to change type of _initialValue in RawAutocomplete and Autocomplete to T? instead of TextEditingValue? and initialize both _textEditingController and _selection in initState:

flutter\lib\src\widgets\autocomplete.dart:

    final T? initialValue;

    void initState() {
      ...
      _selection = widget.initialValue;
      _textEditingController = widget.textEditingController 
      ?? (widget.initialValue != null 
        ? TextEditingController(text: widget.displayStringForOption(widget.initialValue!)) 
        : TextEditingController()
      );
      ...
    }

This will prevent options list to be displayed, if initial value is set and no selection were performed yet.

From my naive understanding, for example, I have heard we should try to keep a class small and has single responsibility, but `EditableTextState` seems to have several thousands of lines of code, with a lot of logic mixed inside.

As a simple example, `EditableTextState` has the following fields and functions:

```dart
Timer? _cursorTimer;
AnimationController get _cursorBlinkOpacityController;
AnimationController? _backingCursorBlinkOpacityController;
...
_startCursorBlink() {...}
_onCursorTick() {...}
_stopCursorBlink() {...}
_startOrStopCursorTimerIfNeeded() {...}
```

which seems like they are all related to cursor, and may be extracted to something like `class _CursorBlinkRelatedLogicAndState { ... }`.

I have guessed there may be some reasons: Maximize performance (since any extra object will cause a few bytes), or indeed the current code is simpler (if the refactored code is even more weird), or just because Flutter is growing so fast and popular that the codebase grows naturally and become this and nobody has had time to refactor it.

I am happy to make a PR (when I am on vacation) if the refactor is helpful. Please correct me if I am wrong!

Cross-posted in discord: https://discord.com/channels/608014603317936148/608021234516754444/1159025196838162524

### Is there an existing issue for this?

- [X] I have searched the [existing issues](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues)
- [X] I have read the [guide to filing a bug](https://flutter.dev/docs/resources/bug-reports)

### Use case

In `focus_manager.dart`, key events are logged in `_focusDebug` checking if `debugFocusChanges` is `true`. This generates a lot of undesired output if I'm only interested in key events.

There is a `debugPrintKeyboardEvents` flag, but when set, there isn't output indicating whether the key event was handled. This output is generated when `debugFocusChanges` is true.

To confirm, run the following code and press any key: 

<details><summary>Code sample</summary>

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';

void main() {
  debugFocusChanges = true;
  runApp(MaterialApp(
    home: Scaffold(body: SizedBox()),
  ));
}
```

</details>



### Proposal

Check for `debugPrintKeyboardEvents` when logging key events instead of `debugFocusChanges`.

### Use case


Currently in `RawAutocomplete`, when the field is changed, `updateOptionsViewVisibility` is only called after the `optionsBuilder` future has resolved:

```
  // Called when _textEditingController changes.
  Future<void> _onChangedField() async {
    final TextEditingValue value = _textEditingController.value;
    final Iterable<T> options = await widget.optionsBuilder(value);
    ...

    // Make sure the options are no longer hidden if the content of the field
    // changes (ignore selection changes).
    if (value.text != _lastFieldText) {
      _lastFieldText = value.text;
      _updateOptionsViewVisibility();
    }
  }

```

This means that users cannot currently display a custom options view while waiting for options from `optionsBuilder`. This might be useful, for example, if the user wants to display a loading message while waiting for options:

![ScreenRecording2024-04-25at9 53 14AM-ezgif com-video-to-gif-converter](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/assets/77553258/e489d156-0be3-46a0-abb6-5d37dd98fab2)


### Proposal

Allow users display a custom options view while waiting for options from `optionsBuilder`.

